**`resolveDates` — trim + normalize to YYYYMMDD:**
```java
private static final DateTimeFormatter DATE_FORMATTER = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyyMMdd");

private RequestDatesContext resolveDates(OnDemandScopeDetailsDto item) {
    // today/yesterday computed once upstream in getVacationDetails (Imen's comment), already YYYYMMDD.
    String today = item.getToday();
    String yesterday = item.getYesterday();

    String historicalDate = normalizeToYyyyMmDd((String) item.getItem().get(HISTORICAL_DATE));
    boolean isHistorical = StringUtils.isNotBlank(historicalDate);

    return new RequestDatesContext(today, yesterday, historicalDate, isHistorical);
}

/**
 * Guarantees YYYYMMDD. Trims whitespace from the CSV value and, if it arrives in a
 * different shape, re-parses and reformats. AMANDA delivers YYYYMMDD so this is a no-op
 * in the normal case, but it removes any dependency on the upstream value being clean.
 */
private String normalizeToYyyyMmDd(String raw) {
    if (StringUtils.isBlank(raw)) {
        return null;
    }
    String trimmed = raw.trim();
    try {
        return LocalDate.parse(trimmed, DATE_FORMATTER).format(DATE_FORMATTER);
    } catch (DateTimeParseException e) {
        // Already-correct or unexpected format — return trimmed value, log for visibility.
        log.warn("Historical date '{}' not in YYYYMMDD after trim; using as-is", trimmed);
        return trimmed;
    }
}
```

The `Date` field population then just uses `dates.requestDate()` — which is now always `YYYYMMDD`.

